{"id":8643,"date":"2017-12-04T02:30:20","date_gmt":"2017-12-04T10:30:20","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/?p=8643"},"modified":"2024-01-06T03:13:58","modified_gmt":"2024-01-06T11:13:58","slug":"bluejoint-mountain","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/12\/04\/bluejoint-mountain\/","title":{"rendered":"BLUEJOINT MOUNTAIN"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong><em>BLUEJOINT MOUNTAIN<\/em><\/strong>\u00a0 \u00a02326m\u00a0\u00a0 7631\u2019<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> <em>When climbing Mt Faith, Bluejoint seems like the most logical point westward to climb. With a lookout tower, access is simple. It forms the SE corner of Granby Provincial Park.\u00a0<\/em><\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> <strong>Location:<\/strong> Granby 50 kms north of Grand Forks.\u00a0<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Difficulty:<\/strong> B1<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Elevation gain:<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Distance:<\/strong> 11 km &#8211; 8 on the road, 3 on the trail.\u00a0<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Time:<\/strong> 5 hours including 8kms on 4WD road.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Access:<\/strong> 2 hours from Castlegar and the road to Granby good. <\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Season:<\/strong> May into November<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Maps:<\/strong>\u00a082E\/7 and 82E\/8 Deer Park; Boundary Forest District Recreation Map; Kamloops Okanagan Backroad Mapbook.<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Drive<\/strong>:\u00a0Just as you enter Grand Forks from the east and just before the bridge over the Granby River, turn right up the Granby Road.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>0.0<\/strong> Follow the creek north for 40 km to pavements ending at Bunch Grass Hill Road. <\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> 40km. Turn left and drive across the bridge. Immediately on the right is the Burrell Recreation Site. Continue NE and soon a Granby FSR sign show up. <\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> 54km Bluejoint Lookout FSR sign.<\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">57km Continue straight. The road ascends the mountainside, good to about 56kms when branches would scrape the car.<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong>Trail:<\/strong> 8 km of good logging road walking. The last 2 km would have been rough for a 4WD. At the road\u2019s end is a parking\/camping area overlooking the valley (no water). <\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> From here it is an easy but steep 3 kilometres to the summit on a good open alpine trail. The forestry lookout is well-constructed and appears used in the dry season. There is a heli-landing pad and two green repeater towers. <\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"> Views are super to Mt Faith to the SE and Old Glory behind it on the horizon, Gladstone to the south, SW is Mt Almond and Gable Mts and the ridges north of them. To the NW the condos and hotels or Big White are visible. NE are Saddle Mt and parts of the Valkyrs and Valhallas. East are the Norns and Bonningtons.<\/span><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>BLUEJOINT MOUNTAIN\u00a0 \u00a02326m\u00a0\u00a0 7631\u2019 When climbing